Blog: Feminism Through Philosophy¶

Currently, politically, economically, and systematically, women are disadvanted. Because a lot of philosophical writings have shaped the fundamentals of our current economical and political systems, NLP approach to philosopical data will certainly help us understand what issues had been addressed by phisophers and what values were missing. Mostly we will focus on only feminism school here. Are the struggles and claims of women similar or diverse among the feminism philosophers? This is my question to be answered. The feminism school philosophers are as follows:

Publication Date Philosopher Title
1792 Mary Wollstonecraft Vindication Of The Rights Of Woman
1949 Anggela Davis Women, Race, And Class
1981 Simone de Beauvoir The Second Sex


After my analysis among the feminism shcool, we will move on to comparing other schools. Later in this blog, you will see several philosophers mentioned "man" (and associated words) more frequently than "woman" (and associated words) despite gender being irrelevant to the topics of thier focus. This will reveal which topics/values women are marginalized from.

As a whole, I will be disuccing below:

Sentiments & Emotions Score¶

Using NRC data to evaluate the 7 emotions (fear, trust, joy, disgust, anticipation, sadness, surprise) and 2 sentiments (negative, positive), we can assign score index 1 to text whenever there are associated words in it.

" what's new, socrates, to make you leave your usual haunts in the lyceum and spend your time here by the king archon's court?"

Gender Mentioned Flag / Times¶

For futher analysis, the following indices will be computed. Both indices can quantify how many times both genders were mentioned in every text.

  1. Flag: if gender associated words were mentioned in a sentence.
  2. Times: count how many times gender associated words were mentioned in a sentence.

For Flag and Times, the following list will be used to catch and contribute to both indices. Most of the words of course include their plural terms.

fWordsList = ["lady", "ladies", "woman", "women", "female", "females", "grandmother", "grandmothers", "grandma", "grandmas", "mother", "mothers", "sister", "sisters", "mom", "girl", "girls", "wife", "wives", "housewife", "housewives", "madam", "madame", "daughter","daughters", "she", "her", "herself"]
mWordsList = ["man", "men", "gentleman", "gentlemen", "grandfather", "grandgathers", "grandpa", "grandpas", "father", "fathers", "brother", "brothers", "dad", "boy", "boys", "guy", "guys", "husband", "husbands", "son","sons", "he", "his", "him", "himself"]

After the process, you can see, for instance, one sentence had mentioned female associated words 20 times whereas another sentence had mentioned male associated words 26 times.

2. Analysis in Feminism School¶

If you might recall, feminism school/authors have mentioned female associated words in their articles. We would like to dig deeper about their values and claims. Of course, NLP methods will be applied instead of reading the literature reviews. Therefore, the analysis output could be different from what it is in reality. In order to be as insightful as possible, several methodologies will be conducted.

  • Text Complexity
    Despite being from the same school, each author should have their own writing style. We will look at how thier writing styles will vary.
  • Sentiment Analysis
    Using the sentiment and emotion score created earlier, we are going to get the sense of the philosophers' emotions and sentiments through their articles.
  • Most Frequenty Used Words
    Excluding the stopping word("a”, “the”, “is”, “are” and etc), knowing the most frequently used words will be useful information to get to know the topic.
  • Relationship Dynamics
    Based on the result from 3, dispersion plots will give more insight into the relationship between the frequently used words.
  • Article Summarization
    Finally, we will summarize each article by picking up 3 most relevant sentences. The method will be detailed later in the section.
  • Topic Modeling
    In spite of the differnt titles, they should have something in common. Topic modeling can reveal more topics than what we assume from the titles.

Terminology

  • Word Size: the average length of the words that an author uses.
  • Sentence Size: the average length of the sentences.
  • Vocabulary To Text: how much vareity of words are within the text.

All three authors shows around 5 on average for the word size. Like "woman/women," the most heavily used words, could be contributing to this result, or we can assume that an usual word could be 5 characters. In contrast to word size, there seems to be disparity in the sentence size. "Vindication Of The Rights Of Woman" have longer sentences in the article compared with the others.
Whereas the vocabulary to text are all around the same ratio, there is a significant disparity in the sentence size. This can suggest that "Vindication Of The Rights Of Woman" could be a lenghty article to the general public because of the use of repetitive words with longer sentences. "Women, Race, And Class" could be entertaining to read with a more variety of vocabulary in relatively shorter sentences.

Most Frequently Used Words¶

This Word Cloud technique picks the most frequently used words by each feminism philosopher. Because "woman" is obviously frequently used, I removed the word from the output. Therefore, all the frequently used words on the graph could suggest the relevancy to "woman". The relationship between the word "woman" and the other frequently used words will be further analyzed in the next section.

From each article's title and the output of this methodology, we can easily guess what the articles are about.
"The Second Sex" by Beauvoir uses the words "mother", "marriage", "children", "desire", and "sexual". Apart from women being mother figures, this result might infer objectification of women.
"Women, Race, And Class" by Davis uses the words "black", "white", "slave", "right", "suffrage", and "racism". In addition to discussing slavery, the text seems to emphasize black women's rights.
"Vindication Of The Rights Of Woman" by Wollstonecraft uses the words "virtue", "reason", "mind", "affection", "respect", and "children". Although these are somewhat positive words, you can also see nagative words "never" and "without". These negative words usually change from a positive sentence to a negative sentence.Therefore, this text seems to address sort of hopefulness about women's position.

Dynamics of Relationship¶

In the previous analysis, it was easy to get the sense of what the articles' claims are. However, using this dispersion plot, the context behind those words will become more clear because this dispersion plot shows when those words are mentioned. If some words were mentioned very closely, then it could be interpreted that they are related.

For Beauvoir, you can see the when "desire" gets mentioned, "sexual" and "woman" are frequently mentioned compared with "marriage" and "children". This supports the author claims that woman's sexual desire is neither positive nor negative. However, because Beauvoir's article had more positivity, there may be encouragement for women to have more sexual desire.

For Davis, when "suffrage" gets mentioned, "woman", "racism", "black", "white", "right" are frequently mentioned. Therefore, the author may emphasize the right of black woman for their suffrage.

For Wollstonecraft, the dipersion plot shows the equally scattered plots of words. You can observe that "children" gets mentioned when "affection" and "respect" are mentioned. However, negative words "never" and "without" are constantly mentioned simultaneously. This again suggests the opposite meaning of respect, virtue and so forth.


Now we know more about each claim by the philosophers by considering the context.

Article Summarization¶

This text summarization techniques summarize what story each philosopher want to deliver to help our understanding of each article. As previously mentioned, this article summarization picked three most relevant sentences and combined them. The way the sentences were picked was to rank most frequently used words and find a sentence that has the most common words the best.

Most relevant three sentences¶

3. Comparison with Philosophers from Other Schools of Thought¶

Why Do We Need to Look at Other Schools of Thought?¶

So far, we focused on only the feminism school of thought to learn what are the values feminism authors are speaking regarding women.
By looking at other philosophers, we can learn which topics lack mentions of women.
In other words, if a philosopher mentions men a lot more often than women, the values or thoughts are something that woman might be not considered for.

This graph shows "both gender to text ratio of mentions by philosopher".
Obviously, those philosophers who have low ratio for both genders tend to talk about something irrelevant to humans in general. A good example is Phenomenology with a low ratio for both genders.
Therefore, let us pick up non-femnism school philosophers who have high ratio for male mentions - this time, 20% is our threshold.

Most Frequently Used Words¶

These all mentioned men more than 20% to each text while mentioning women less than 5%. Each article has very strong and masucluine words along with their titles. Especially, what some of the articles have in common is that they repeatedly mention "power", "knowledge", and "idea". In fact, in old social philosophy, power was condsidered to be gained by knowledge and idea in the society. Because these words were used along with men, we can get the sense of the main concept that these are the values that men may have been expected to have or been granted in order to strive in human society.

4. Summary¶

In conclusion, as we can see the reuslt of this analysis, there are diverse topics to discuss within feminism. However, many philosphers of this dataset unfortunately chose to mention men over women irrespective of non-gender related topics. Therefore, in the future we hope to see future philosopher will include both men and women when disucssing variety of idea. Hopefully this will create more inclusive philosophical school of thgouhts.
